  "prompt": "Relation between change in celcius to change in fahrenhiet?",
  "response": "To understand the relationship between a change in Celsius and a change in Fahrenheit, we need to consider the conversion formula between the two temperature scales. The formula to convert Celsius to Fahrenheit is:\n\n\\[ F = \\frac{9}{5}C + 32 \\]\n\nWhen we talk about a change in temperature, the constant 32 (which represents the freezing point of water in Fahrenheit) becomes irrelevant because it's the same for both the initial and final temperatures. Therefore, we can focus on the ratio of the change in Fahrenheit (\\(\\Delta F\\)) to the change in Celsius (\\(\\Delta C\\)):\n\n\\[ \\Delta F = \\frac{9}{5} \\Delta C \\]\n\nThis tells us that a change in Celsius is related to a change in Fahrenheit by a factor of \\(\\frac{9}{5}\\). Specifically:\n\n- A change of 1\u00b0C is equivalent to a change of \\(\\frac{9}{5}\\)\u00b0F, or 1.8\u00b0F.\n- Conversely, a change of 1\u00b0F is equivalent to a change of \\(\\frac{5}{9}\\)\u00b0F, or approximately 0.556\u00b0C.\n\nSo, the key relationship is:\n\n\\[ \\Delta F = 1.8 \\times \\Delta C \\]\n\\[ \\Delta C = \\frac{\\Delta F}{1.8} \\]\n\nThis relationship holds true for any change in temperature, regardless of the starting temperature.",
